Angels One Five is a 1952 film directed by George More O'Ferrall, and
starring Jack Hawkins, Michael Denison, Dulcie Gray, John Gregson, Cyril
Raymond, and also featuring Bill Everett. The plot centres on a young fighter
pilot immediately before and during the Battle of Britain in the Second World
War. Some scenes in the film were shot at RAF Uxbridge, home to a
wartime operations room.

"Angels One Five" refers to RAF radio procedure words, from the Second
World War, meaning an altitude of 15,000 feet.
